00:01.240 --> 00:09.040
Get your voice level. Okay, I'll give you a level. If we shadows have offended,
think that this and all is mended, that you have but slumbered here while these

00:09.040 --> 00:17.380
visions did appear. And this week, an idle theme, no more yielding but a dream,
gentles. Do not reprehend. If you pardon, I will mend. And as I am an honest

00:17.380 --> 00:24.620
puck, if I have unearned luck, not escaping the serpent's tongue, I will make
amends there long. Else the puck a liar call, and so goodnight unto you all.

00:25.060 --> 00:36.440
Give me your hand if we be friends, and Robin shall restore amends. Yeah, I'm
getting ready. We can go. Okay. Yeah, the tape is rolling, so we're going to go

00:36.440 --> 00:47.460
ahead now. Mr. Paul, you've written of how you grew up with science fiction,
reading The Pulse, organizing clubs, editing fanzines, and so forth. Could you

00:47.460 --> 00:56.860
recall what it was that attracted you to science fiction so completely at such
an early age? Well, I think it was basically the adventure, the kind of science

00:56.860 --> 01:07.620
fiction that was being published around 1930, when I first got in touch with it,
when I first discovered that it existed, was mostly space opera and gimmick

01:07.620 --> 01:17.640
stories and the stories about exciting, adventurous exploits all over the
galaxy. And that was in the middle of the Great Depression, and science fiction

01:17.640 --> 01:21.340
looked an awful lot better to me than the real world that I could see.

01:27.840 --> 01:36.960
Okay, I believe your first story was published around 1937. Is that correct,
around that time? The first thing I had published was a poem. It was an amazing

01:36.960 --> 01:49.980
story. I wrote it in 1935, and it was accepted in 1936, and published in 1937,
and paid for in 1938. So somewhere in there I became a professional writer. The

01:49.980 --> 01:58.540
first story, I think, was probably in 1938. It was a collaboration with another
writer, and it appeared in Astounding, the magazine that's now called Analog.

02:00.800 --> 02:10.400
Could you explain just a little bit about what the Futurians were, and your part
in the organization? Well, science fiction has some special traits, and one of

02:10.400 --> 02:21.500
them is that its readers heard together as much as they can. They formed fan
clubs and associations and correspondence groups and so on. And in New York

02:21.500 --> 02:32.980
City, there were quite a few science fiction fans, and about 25 or 30, most of
whom wanted to be writers, formed a club called the Futurians. There were people

02:32.980 --> 02:45.460
like Cyril Karnblist and Isaac Asimov and Damon Knight and myself and quite a
few others. Don Walheim, who's now the head of Daw Books as an editor, and, you

02:45.460 --> 02:53.580
know, batches of others who really desperately wanted to write science fiction
or edit science fiction or something like that. Quite a few of them acted out

02:53.580 --> 03:05.080
their childhood fantasies and did it. And I'm not quite sure why the Futurians
produced more science fiction writers than most of the other clubs. It probably

03:05.080 --> 03:13.980
has something to do with size. New York had a bigger pool of talent to draw
from. The Los Angeles group also produced quite a few, including Ray Bradbury

03:13.980 --> 03:25.020
and Larry Niven and several others. Did you help each other in your writing? Was
it sort of a brotherhood kind of thing where you aided each other? It was partly

03:25.020 --> 03:38.920
help and partly one-upmanship and putting each other down. We did discuss each
other's work a lot, and I guess in the process of criticizing it, there was a

03:38.920 --> 03:48.780
lot of help given. I think the biggest factor that made it easier for a lot of
us to go on with writing was just the knowledge that other people were doing it,

03:49.500 --> 04:01.120
and also the fact that we collaborated a lot. We remedied each other's
deficiencies by writing, I mean by collaborating on single stories. And although

04:01.120 --> 04:09.380
most of the stories were not very good, we did learn something by seeing how
other people would tackle the same subjects we were writing about.

04:13.000 --> 04:20.880
You're uniquely qualified, I think, to comment on science fiction since you've
seen it from so many perspectives, as a fan, an author, an agent, an editor, and

04:20.880 --> 04:30.020
so forth. You started the editing part of it when you were 19 years old, I
think. Is that right? I was lucky enough to fall into a job as a professional

04:30.020 --> 04:40.700
magazine editor. When I was 19, I had asked. An editor I knew, because I'd been
trying to sell him stories without success, if he needed an assistant, and he

04:40.700 --> 04:49.200
was kind enough not to laugh out loud. I didn't know at the time that not very
many science fiction magazine editors could afford assistance. But he mentioned

04:49.200 --> 04:57.060
to me another publishing company that was expanding and suggested I get in touch
with them. So I did. It was popular publications, one of the biggest pulp houses

04:57.060 --> 05:07.340
of the time. And they were expanding, and they gave me a job at $10 a week to
edit two professional science fiction magazines. $10 wasn't so bad. They hired

05:07.340 --> 05:17.800
other editors for nothing at the same time. And most of the material you got
then was the pulp kind of stuff? It was mostly pulp, but it included a lot of

05:17.800 --> 05:26.320
the writers who are the mainstays of the field now. I published a lot of Isaac
Asimov's stuff because we were close friends. A few of Robert A. Heinlein's

05:26.320 --> 05:37.240
stories that his primary market, John Campbell, for one reason or other, didn't
want to print. And Henry Kuttner and A. G. Van Root and Cleve Cartmill and L.

05:37.360 --> 05:47.940
Sprague DeCamp and most of the people who were writing at that time wound up in
my magazine, not always with their best stories. In fact, very often with their

05:47.940 --> 05:56.860
worst stories, because I wasn't paying very much. I had a budget of about half a
cent a word. Yeah, and one of the other lines of work that you got into, I

05:56.860 --> 06:06.300
remember, was as an advertising copywriter, which brings up to my mind the novel
The Space Merchants. Well, actually, The Space Merchants was sort of responsible

06:06.300 --> 06:17.980
for it. When I was in the Army, in the Air Force, in World War II, I had some
spare time on my hands in Italy, and I decided to write a novel. And the most

06:17.980 --> 06:28.160
interesting subject I could think of was the advertising industry. So I wrote a
whole novel about advertising. Very bad novel. After the war was over, I took it

06:28.160 --> 06:37.720
out and looked at it and realized that it was pretty bad, and one of its great
defects was that I didn't know anything about advertising. So I went to the New

06:37.720 --> 06:47.940
York Sunday Times and looked in the classified section, found a couple of people
advertising jobs in advertising, and applied and got one of them and spent about

06:47.940 --> 06:58.940
three years as an advertising copywriter. And during that time, I looked over
this old novel again and realized that it had many more faults and ignorance.

06:59.900 --> 07:08.660
And I burned it, and I had all the basic information about advertising and no
novel to put it in. So I thought of writing a science fiction novel, and it

07:08.660 --> 07:19.920
turned out to be The Space Merchants. And Cyril Kornblith was a close friend of
mine. We'd collaborated before the war, before we both went into service. And

07:19.920 --> 07:32.260
after I had written about a third of it, because a magazine editor wanted it in
a hurry, I asked Cyril if he wanted to help me with it, and he and I

07:32.260 --> 07:42.440
collaborated on it from that on. What was your normal method of collaboration?
How did you work out your scenarios for the future? We didn't work them out in

07:42.440 --> 07:53.420
very great detail ahead of time. Mostly what Cyril and I did was do, let's see,
we wrote seven novels and a number of short stories together. Generally

07:53.420 --> 08:02.740
speaking, what we did after the war, after the space merchants, and we began
writing novels more often than short stories. Cyril would come out to my house

08:02.740 --> 08:14.520
in Red Bank, New Jersey, where we kept the room for him with his own typewriter,
and we'd sit around and talk for a while and discuss general areas we were

08:14.520 --> 08:23.380
interested in writing about, maybe some characters. And then we'd flip a coin,
and the loser would go up to the third floor and write the first four pages, and

08:23.380 --> 08:33.260
he'd come down and say, you're on the other person and write the next four
pages. And if you do that about 25 or 30 times, you have the rough draft of a

08:33.260 --> 08:43.720
complete novel. Everything got radically rewritten after that because the rough
draft was pretty rough, but structurally it was all there. Going back to the

08:43.720 --> 08:53.460
space merchants, can you think of any more successful book in the history of
science fiction than that one? Oh, I'm sure there are a lot that are more

08:53.460 --> 09:02.940
successful, depending on how you measure it. Certainly the H.G. Wells books were
far more successful and far more noteworthy in that they influenced far more

09:02.940 --> 09:12.300
people. But the space merchants hasn't done badly. It's been translated into 45
or so languages and has been continuously in print for, let's see, it's now

09:12.300 --> 09:23.100
almost 30 years. You mentioned that the movie rights had been sold and there was
some sort of a black market tape or something of a dramatic production of it.

09:23.200 --> 09:32.460
Could you talk about that for just a moment? Well, when the book came out, the
Columbia Workshop of the Air made an adaptation of it. There was very little

09:32.460 --> 09:42.420
television at that time, so it was a radio adaptation. It was a two-part radio
play, which someone illicitly dubbed, and tapes are available of it. I've heard

09:42.420 --> 09:53.900
that. Unfortunately, they don't pay royalties. And about 10 or 15 years after
its publication, a British outfit bought the film rights. They bought them

09:53.900 --> 10:01.840
outright, and they paid what struck me at the time as a fantastic amount of
money for them. In fact, they had to get the approval of the Bank of England to

10:01.840 --> 10:15.060
transfer that much foreign exchange. But they never made it. I'm not quite sure
why. They not only didn't make it, they refused to listen to offers from other

10:15.060 --> 10:26.120
producers who wanted to make it. And it just bogged down somewhere in the red
tape. I think there's a chance that it will be made in some form now because the

10:26.120 --> 10:37.920
British outfit has loosened up and is willing to consider offers. But so far, I
know of no firm plan. Mm-hmm. There's one question I can never avoid asking an

10:37.920 --> 10:46.280
author. I'm sure you get these all the time and I'm not sure how you respond to
them. But regarding the ending of the novel, did you intend for that to be

10:46.280 --> 10:54.440
optimistic that we're going to get a new start on Venus, maybe perhaps construct
a better society? Was that the intention there, or did you leave it ambiguous? I

10:54.440 --> 11:05.080
left it ambiguous partly because I wasn't feeling very positive at the time. The
novel was written in 1952 and thereabouts, which was a pretty grimy period in

11:05.080 --> 11:17.100
the history of this country. It was the McCarthy years and the Cold War years,
and things did not look too... They didn't look even as good as they do now, as

11:17.100 --> 11:26.380
a matter of fact. So I wasn't feeling optimistic. I didn't mean to foreclose the
possibility of a happy ending. Actually, the novel had two endings. There was a

11:26.380 --> 11:36.220
different ending in the magazine version, more upbeat, but less organically
related to the rest of the novel. It was put in at the insistence of the

11:36.220 --> 11:46.220
magazine editor. Mm-hmm. Many readers, of course, have noticed a very strong
social element in your work. You have much to say about United States society

11:46.220 --> 11:56.640
and culture and so forth, and I believe you've even been involved in politics.
Have you seen yourself in the role of a preacher or moralist with warnings and

11:56.640 --> 12:08.820
science fiction as sort of a pulpit, maybe, or a soapbox sort of a thing to
satirize with? Oh, sure. I think that every writer who really has any interest

12:08.820 --> 12:19.360
in what he's doing feels that he has something to say. There's a remark, I don't
remember the source of it, that the proper title of every book is really How to

12:19.360 --> 12:30.420
Be More Like Me. And I think that's something. I think that writers are
preachers and educators and polemicists and propagandists. It isn't always

12:30.420 --> 12:40.760
political, and it isn't always overt, but if it isn't there, the novel doesn't
say anything. My own interests have been fairly heavily social and political

12:40.760 --> 12:49.760
most of my life. I was active, as you mentioned, in a lot of political things at
one time or another. I even wrote a book called Practical Politics, which is

12:49.760 --> 13:04.760
sort of a how-to-do-it manual of how to make the political apparatus work for
whatever cause is interesting. But I do not go out of my way to preach. It just,

13:04.760 --> 13:17.600
I guess, colors everything I say because a lot of myself, and as of every other
writer I know, goes into what I'm writing. Do you think that science fiction has

13:17.600 --> 13:27.180
peculiar qualifications to act as a vehicle for social comment? I think science
fiction has special qualifications to act as a vehicle for discussing anything

13:27.180 --> 13:36.400
that affects the human being. It's a way of looking at the human race from
outside, objectively. It's a way of, it's a sort of game-playing mechanism for

13:36.400 --> 13:45.300
seeing what would happen to human beings under conditions that haven't occurred
yet but are very possible. And I think that that's probably one of the strongest

13:45.300 --> 13:56.040
factors accounting for the continual growth and interest in science fiction that
seems to have been going on as long as I've been alive. Okay. In some of your

13:56.040 --> 14:07.360
recent works, say, Jam and Man Plus, you describe some bad political systems, I
think, where there's a lot of deception, selfish motives, war. I think even in

14:07.360 --> 14:18.680
Jam, there was annihilation of the earth. Does that concentration on the bad
aspects of society come from your view of the world? No, I'm really Pollyanna.

14:18.960 --> 14:29.940
I'm a great optimist about the world. I think that we're in for some terrible
times, and I don't think that most of us will enjoy much of what happens in the

14:29.940 --> 14:39.120
next few years. But I think in the long run, the human race will straighten
itself out and learn to be able to live better with each other. But as far as

14:39.120 --> 14:48.280
writing a novel is concerned, it's not too interesting to write about a utopia.
I mean, what are you going to say about a bunch of people who walk around in

14:48.280 --> 15:01.700
togas and eat whole wheat bread and never have any bad thoughts? It's much more
interesting to paint the disasters that may occur as a sort of... I think it's

15:01.700 --> 15:10.160
Kingsley Amos who calls that kind of science fiction cautionary literature. It's
not saying what will happen. It's just warning what might happen if we don't

15:10.160 --> 15:21.740
watch out. Okay, I'd like to ask the same question about Jam that I did about
space merchants. The ending of it. I took it as hopeful, the part human, part

15:21.740 --> 15:29.580
alien society, which you envision at the end of the book. I took that as
hopeful. Would I be misreading it? No, I think that it's hopeful. I think that

15:29.580 --> 15:41.780
what I was trying to say in Jam was perhaps a little more overt preaching than I
usually intend. And I'm not sure that it came across the way I intended it to.

15:41.780 --> 15:51.780
But the subtitle of Jam is The Making of a Utopia. And what I was trying to say
in the novel is that you can't really plan a utopia. You cannot construct a

15:51.780 --> 16:06.040
society that will make everybody happy and productive and glad to be alive.
Because the happiness, satisfaction, productivity are not a state. They're a

16:06.040 --> 16:21.360
process. And no rigid system can survive giving people maximum opportunities to
realize their potential without being flexible and changeable. Okay, and then in

16:21.360 --> 16:31.500
Man Plus, what fascinated me about that book was your examination, the way you
did it. You examined machine intelligence. Do you think that's going to be

16:31.500 --> 16:41.560
possible? The computers that you envision there are linking up and working to
survive? And sort of taking off? I think it's an undecided question. I'm not

16:41.560 --> 16:54.200
sure which... It's a 50-50 chance, in my opinion, whether machine intelligence
can ever develop these sort of independent, self-defining goals that human

16:54.200 --> 17:05.600
beings can't. But I don't think it's impossible. It's just that machines have
not yet got that smart. What I'm pretty sure of is that machines right now are

17:05.600 --> 17:18.060
doing things that 50 years ago one would have described as showing human
intelligence. They solve problems very well. They even do creative things like

17:19.280 --> 17:30.000
composing music in any style you like, or writing poetry. It's true that the
music and the poetry aren't very good, but most human-generated music and poetry

17:30.000 --> 17:38.420
is not very good either. And I think that maybe better programs can be written
for machines and they can be more creative. But I think when that happens,

17:38.660 --> 17:50.080
people will simply redefine that activity as no longer a symptom of
intelligence. Okay, the cyborg that you mentioned in that book, too, do you

17:50.080 --> 17:57.980
think man will be partners with machine in that sort of way, too? I think it's
quite possible. I didn't make up the cyborg. The term and the concept was

17:57.980 --> 18:12.460
invented by two Air Force or NASA, I've forgotten which researchers, in 1958 or
thereabouts. And it's been used widely in a lot of places, but I didn't make it

18:12.460 --> 18:23.380
up. I think that we already see cyborgs in the sense that a lot of people have
mechanical parts keeping them alive, pacemakers and artificial plastic veins and

18:23.380 --> 18:33.440
arteries and so on, not to mention things like glass eyes and prosthetic limbs
and false teeth and so on. And I think we also see a sort of intellectual

18:33.440 --> 18:46.440
symbiotic like the cyborg in the link-up between human beings and computers.
Computers do not solve problems, do not make up problems and solve them, but

18:46.440 --> 18:54.320
they make it possible for human beings to do that sort of thing in a fraction of
the time it used to take them. Therefore, they make the human beings effectively

18:54.320 --> 19:06.700
more intelligent than they were. Okay, that leads me up to Gateway, which is one
of my favorite books. I think you've also written or said that it's one of your

19:06.700 --> 19:16.180
favorite novels. It's the novel that I cared most about. I'm not entirely
pleased with anything I've written, and I'm very displeased with a lot of what

19:16.180 --> 19:24.400
I've written. But Gateway comes as close to being the way I would like it to be
as any novel I've ever written. Now, I think I noticed this. I'm sure many

19:24.400 --> 19:33.920
readers did, too. In fact, you've commented on it. There's a departure in style,
I think, from your other work. What were the influences that both caused the

19:33.920 --> 19:42.460
idea of the book, perhaps, and also the different kind of style you used in it?
Well, one of the big things in Gateway was that I was under no pressure from

19:42.460 --> 19:51.080
anyone but myself to do it the way I thought it should be done. I had my
publisher at that time, my principal publisher, was a man named Ian Valentine,

19:52.260 --> 20:00.480
who offered me a contract with a substantial advance to write a novel without
saying what the novel was going to be and without imposing any deadline on when

20:00.480 --> 20:11.860
I had to deliver it. So I didn't have to discuss it with an editor ahead of time
or write an outline and limit myself and the opportunities I could take. And I

20:11.860 --> 20:24.640
didn't have the pressure of getting it delivered at a specific date to make me
rush it through. And actually, it took me, I think, six years from the time I

20:24.640 --> 20:33.060
signed the contract until I delivered it. And I had been mulling it over for
several years before that. All in all, I think the book was something like ten

20:33.060 --> 20:47.060
years in the gestation. And also, it's not possible for a writer to produce at
the same level all the time. I don't know why. There are times when I write

20:47.060 --> 20:58.580
better than others. I can't relate them to any outside influence or to my
resolution to do well or anything like that. I just know that sometimes it comes

20:58.580 --> 21:09.920
out better than other times. And Gateway, I think, is one of the times that it
came out very well. I wish I could say the same of all of my books. Did you say

21:09.920 --> 21:18.900
the New Wave was an influence on the way you wrote that book, the so-called New
Wave in science fiction? New Wave was an attempt, I guess, 15 years ago or more,

21:19.060 --> 21:26.080
of a number of writers to break away from the traditional kinds of science
fiction. In fact, most of them didn't want to call it science fiction anymore.

21:26.260 --> 21:36.720
They wanted to call it speculative fiction or call it nothing at all. And they
were interested primarily in writing about inner space rather than outer space

21:36.720 --> 21:49.460
and secondarily, a lot of them in things like the drug culture and rock music
and so on. But in the rather bitter internal struggle that went on in science

21:49.460 --> 21:57.840
fiction, a lot of people taking sides one way or the other. I think everyone was
deeply affected. And the New Wave, if nothing else, taught a bunch of old

21:57.840 --> 22:09.500
dinosaurs like Azimov and Heinlein and me, that there were non-traditional ways
of constructing a novel. You see, most of us had grown up when science fiction

22:09.500 --> 22:17.820
was in the pulp magazines and most of it was written according to some variant
of a pulp formula. Well, it turned out that wasn't necessary. And I think the

22:17.820 --> 22:27.940
New Wave is responsible for teaching us that. When you were writing Gateway,
when you conceived of the idea during that gestation period, did you intend for

22:27.940 --> 22:34.900
there to be a sequel to it at that time? No, I did not intend for there to be a
sequel to it until it was published and people began telling me I ought to write

22:34.900 --> 22:45.200
a sequel. That's what I was interested in. In other words, were these fans, you
responded to fan desires in that respect? Largely to fan desires and also to my

22:45.200 --> 22:57.560
publisher who sat on me and insisted. I wasn't too hard to convince, but I did
not have any such plans. I know that Gateway leaves a lot of questions

22:57.560 --> 23:09.040
unanswered and suggests a lot of things that are not made explicit in the novel.
And I did all that on purpose, but not for the sake of preparing the way for a

23:09.040 --> 23:19.820
sequel, but just because I think that's a characteristic of a lot of good
science fiction. When you finish the story, you think of things that let you

23:19.820 --> 23:29.500
write your own stories after it. I mean, that's the sort of thing that Arthur
Clarke does very well. And I try to do it whenever I can. And it just turned out

23:29.500 --> 23:37.640
that there was a lot of public pressure to write a sequel. There's also been
public pressure to write another sequel, and I'm just about to sign a contract

23:37.640 --> 23:47.640
to do that, but I swear I had no such intention when I finished Beyond the Blue
Event Horizon. That's what I was going to ask you. There were still some

23:47.640 --> 23:54.820
questions about the Heechi that were open for exploration, and I wondered if
you'd considered another novel about them. I considered it, and just a few weeks

23:54.820 --> 24:03.040
ago, I yielded the pressure from my publisher and said I would sign a contract
for another book. I don't plan to go on beyond that. I don't want to do Habit

24:03.040 --> 24:14.460
Kistola meet the Heechi, or Habit and the Heechi go to Hawaii, or whatever.
That's going to be the end of it as far as I'm concerned, but I will write one

24:14.460 --> 24:23.020
more. So many authors are doing trilogies these days. I thought that maybe you'd
started out with that idea way back. No, not me. A lot of them do, and I kind of

24:23.020 --> 24:31.900
resent it because I think mostly it's unfair to the reader to give them part of
a story. I don't think that's true of either Gateway or Beyond the Blue. I think

24:31.900 --> 24:42.400
they stand up by themselves. Okay, I'd like to switch for just a few minutes to
some questions about your time as an editor. I think it was during the 60s you

24:42.400 --> 24:51.220
served as the editor of Galaxy and some of its satellite publications. And
probably the best science fiction of a decade went through you in that magazine,

24:51.380 --> 25:01.880
the best magazine of science fiction. I was interested in how much influence you
had on the authors, you know, your method of encouraging, coaxing, how you

25:01.880 --> 25:12.240
worked with them to get the material you did. What's different with different
authors, the thing that I know best about how to be an editor is that you cannot

25:12.240 --> 25:23.280
have a general policy and apply it to everybody and hope it will work in every
case because writers are very diverse human beings. Some of them respond to long

25:23.280 --> 25:35.420
letters of criticism and suggestions and patting on the back or beating over the
head and some of them do not want any outside influence at all. One of my

25:35.420 --> 25:46.060
favorite writers told me early in our relationship that he was willing to have
me buy some stories and reject others but he didn't want to hear why. If I sent

25:46.060 --> 25:55.600
it back, just send it back and say no and not tell him what I didn't like about
it because that upset him. Other writers wanted to know in great detail not only

25:55.600 --> 26:04.720
what I didn't like but what I did like. And also, there are some writers who are
very responsive to money and some to whom money means nothing at all. Not that

26:04.720 --> 26:15.380
they are immune to it but they don't want to think in those terms. And there are
some writers who respond to a lot of personal attention and some who really want

26:15.380 --> 26:25.300
to be left alone. And I had to find out something about each writer to find out
the best way to deal with them. I can't say I was always successful either.

26:25.300 --> 26:36.780
There are a number of writers that I think I should have been able to get more
good material from and didn't. And I just missed the combination in those cases.

26:38.940 --> 26:48.220
An editor in that position, the kind of position you had, I would assume that a
lot of stories get published because of the editor's help and whatever kinds of

26:48.220 --> 26:55.960
encouragement he gives that would not have been published otherwise. Quite a
few. Yeah, especially quite a few stories come to be written because an editor

26:55.960 --> 27:05.480
says, listen, you've got a notion here that you are throwing away and you really
should expand it. John Campbell was superb at that sort of thing. Some of the

27:05.480 --> 27:17.680
best stories he published were the result of his telling a writer that he had an
idea that he didn't realize he had and then getting the writer to write it. And

27:17.680 --> 27:28.120
I tried to do that as much as I could too. But writers do not always know where
their ideas come from and do not always know how to deal with outside

27:28.120 --> 27:39.860
suggestions. There's one very good writer who always wanted comments and
suggestions who I finally decided I shouldn't ever give any to because the only

27:39.860 --> 27:49.240
thing he ever did was not to rewrite a story the way I suggested it but to throw
it away and write a whole new one. I was never able to get him to rewrite a line

27:49.240 --> 28:00.300
and as a result there are probably 10 or 15 stories of his that will never be
published because he just threw them away. Hmm. When you I think IF was one of

28:00.300 --> 28:08.680
the magazines you worked with when you were with Galaxy. Galaxy and IF and a
couple of others. Yeah. Did you get Larry Niven's first story in that IF

28:08.680 --> 28:18.260
magazine? Mm-hmm. I published his first story which is a very short one and for
which he got a very short paycheck and his next one was a little longer and he

28:18.260 --> 28:27.300
got a little more and the next one was quite a lot longer and he got quite a lot
more and Larry said that if it hadn't been for those three events in that order

28:27.300 --> 28:37.260
he could not have gone on being a writer. So I take some pride in the fact that
I was instrumental in making it possible for him to devote his time to writing.

28:37.860 --> 28:48.720
Were those first stories were they the hard science fiction type that he's noted
for? Yes. Larry has always been best at writing hard science fiction. One or two

28:48.720 --> 29:00.860
of them I suggested to him but mostly it was just a matter of encouraging him to
do his own thing. The neutron star of the first Hugo he won was a story I

29:00.860 --> 29:12.400
suggested to him. Okay. Also you worked at Bannam Books for a while. Do I
remember correctly that you were the one who published Delaney's Dahlgren? Yes

29:12.400 --> 29:22.800
indeed. After every other publisher in America had turned it down or at least
