29:41.700 --> 29:54.580
the book knows that it's a complicated and difficult book but it was also the
work of a writer who I consider to be one of the most talented in the field and

29:54.580 --> 30:05.280
a writer who considered it to be his best work. So all my misgivings were
overcome by the fact that I had that much trust in Delaney. I didn't really

30:05.280 --> 30:14.120
think it would do as well as it did. I thought it might get through a printing
of a hundred thousand copies and then rest for a while and then word of mouth

30:14.120 --> 30:22.460
would make it a bigger book but actually it took off immediately. I don't know
how many copies it sold. It's over half a million and maybe a million. Was there

30:22.460 --> 30:31.020
much revision you suggested for that book or was it pretty much... I didn't ask
them to do a thing to it. My big concern was to make sure that the typesetters

30:31.020 --> 30:42.100
said it exactly the way he wrote it. Yeah. Do you think in those kinds of
positions that you had and maybe other editors who worked a few years in the

30:42.100 --> 30:50.620
past, can an editor today have as much influence as he could in the past, say
you or John Campbell or somebody? I don't think so. One of the reasons I gave up

30:50.620 --> 31:04.280
editing was that it seemed to me to have become less a matter of personal work
by one editor and more and more of a committee matter. There are editors who are

31:04.280 --> 31:15.380
very good at what they're doing and do some things far better than I ever could.
But it's a different kind of thing. It's no longer a one-man operation or a one

31:15.380 --> 31:28.100
-woman operation. It's now big business. When I began writing science fiction,
even a magazine like Astounding, which was the preeminent thing in the field,

31:28.700 --> 31:42.820
was paying to all writers combined over the course of a year probably less than
$10,000. And now any novel can expect to get that much. Some of them get ten

31:42.820 --> 31:55.420
times that much or even a hundred times that much. So it's got to be quite big
business. Okay, let me make another little switch here to your work as an agent.

31:56.340 --> 32:08.740
I was interested in the innovation or the way that you paid your authors. Could
you explain how that worked? Well, when I was an agent, it occurred to me that a

32:08.740 --> 32:17.780
lot of my writers were, they needed their checks to live on. And consequently,
they were trying to write stories that they thought someone would buy quickly

32:17.780 --> 32:28.800
and pay for very well rather than the things that I thought they were really
good at. So I made an arrangement with a number of them, I think about 20 or 25

32:28.800 --> 32:37.440
at the top, that they could write anything they wanted to and I would advance
them a certain amount per word as soon as I got the manuscript I would wait for

32:37.440 --> 32:46.620
it to sell. And as a result, I think that a lot of them were writing pretty well
at that time. Cyril Karnbluth was one of them, Damon Knight was one of them, and

32:46.620 --> 32:57.320
Robert Checkley and a few others and I think they were just about doing their
best work under those conditions. However, it turned out to be more of a

32:57.320 --> 33:03.240
financial burden than I could bear and consequently I managed to lose about $30
,000 as an agent.

33:06.040 --> 33:14.560
I would imagine though that you kept many authors going and we have many books
and stories today because of that method. I think so. I mean, I'm willing to

33:14.560 --> 33:23.000
take credit for that because I believe it to be so. And I do think that it's a
very good way to operate, but as far as I know, no other agent has ever done it.

33:23.520 --> 33:36.380
And I'm sure I know why, because it does tend to be a big drain on capital and
if you don't have a lot of capital, it can't be done. I was sort of fascinated

33:36.380 --> 33:48.020
to read the publishing history the first time it was published, the book Mission
of Gravity by Hal Clement. If I understand right, you were the agent that sold

33:48.020 --> 33:58.560
the book to Campbell? Yeah, well, Hal Clement had written the book all by
himself. He was one of the writers who functioned best when left alone. and all

33:58.560 --> 34:01.620
by himself had submitted it to a prize novel contest

34:04.420 --> 34:11.900
run by one of the semi-pro publishers of the time and it got stuck there and
couldn't get loose of it. So my first big problem was to get it away from them,

34:12.500 --> 34:21.540
which took quite a lot of effort. Second problem was that when I submitted it to
Campbell, who was obviously the right person to publish it, he sent it back. He

34:21.540 --> 34:30.180
said, pretty good stuff that you should know, Fred, that there's a difference
between a novel that reads well as a book and a novel that reads well as a

34:30.180 --> 34:41.600
serial and this one just does not break as a serial. So I knew he was wrong and
I knew I couldn't argue him out of it and so I looked at the manuscript which

34:41.600 --> 34:52.160
was, I think, 270 pages long or something like that and I counted up to page 90
and drew a line under a paragraph there and counted up to page 180 and drew a

34:52.160 --> 35:01.300
line under a paragraph there and had my secretary retype a couple of pages on
each side of each line saying at the bottom of the first part end of part one

35:01.300 --> 35:11.340
and the beginning of the second part beginning of part two and I let it sit for
a couple weeks and I sent it back to John and he bought it. I didn't tell him

35:11.340 --> 35:19.440
that it had been rewritten which it hadn't I just sent it back and he bought it
and published it and it turned out to be very nearly the most popular serial

35:19.440 --> 35:29.740
analog ever astounding or analog whatever it was at the time ever run. One of
the things that I'm convinced of about being an agent is that you shouldn't let

35:29.740 --> 35:40.980
editors make mistakes. If they reject something they really should buy you
should find some way of getting them to reverse themselves. Well that was a that

35:40.980 --> 35:46.260
might have been a close call. Do you think that book would have had trouble
being published? Not a bit. It certainly would have been published somewhere

35:46.260 --> 35:59.200
else but the right place for it I thought was in astounding because it was the
prestige magazine at the time. Okay. I believe I read also were you were you

35:59.200 --> 36:10.700
Isaac Asimov's agent at one time? Yes I was. And you what sort of helped him
from the transition from the magazines to book publication? Yeah. I persuaded

36:10.700 --> 36:23.940
him to think in terms of writing books and it wasn't easy because Isaac was
quite convinced that he wasn't a book writer and the particular manuscript that

36:23.940 --> 36:31.680
I wanted to sell as a book he didn't like very much. He'd written it for a
